Two balls, of masses $m_A = m_B$ are suspended as shown below. The lighter ball is pulled away to a $66^\circ$ angle with the vertical and released. (a) What is the velocity of the lighter ball before impact? (b) What is the velocity of each ball after the elastic collision? (c) What
will be the maximum
height of each ball after
the elastic collision?
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=5cm]{bruhhh.png}
\end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
\item Using conservation of energy, we have
    $$\frac 12 mv^2 = mg R (1 - \cos \theta) \implies v = \sqrt{2gR(1- \cos \theta)} = 2.02\,\unit{m/s}.$$
    \item Because they are equal mass, they will just exchange velocities, so $$v_{A,f} = 0, v_{B,f} = 2.02\,\unit{m/s}.$$
    \item By symmetry, the B ball will go up to $66^\circ$, which corresponds to $21\,\unit{cm}$ up.
\end{anum}

By conservation of momentum, the sum of the momentum vectors of the two balls must add to the original momentum vector of the first ball. However, since the masses of the balls are equal, this is equivalent to the final velocity vectors of the two adding to the original velocity vectors. This is shown graphically below.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=5cm]{velocity_addition.png}
\end{center}
    Furthermore, by conservation of energy, we have $v_1^2 + v_2^2 = v_i^2$, so by pythagorean's theorem, the two final velocity vectors must form right angles with each other, and we are done.
